post_text:
We regret to inform you that the 29th Stew & Auction on April 18 will be cancelled. This decision was made in order to adhere to Federal, State, and school district health and safety policies in the wake of the COVID-19 outbreak.

This is an unprecedented year for agricultural education, and Winona FFA is not immune to the changes. However, we will come back stronger than ever next year!

State LDE Contest weekend was a success! Out of 1,075 chapters in Texas:
Ag Issues Forum: 9th Place
Greenhand Quiz: 9th Place
Senior Quiz: Top 20 in the state

This marks the first time since 2007 that Winona FFA has had 3 teams at the State LDE.

The final picture is with our sister chapter, Center Point FFA, which was 1st in Sr. Quiz and 2nd in Greenhand Quiz.

Thank you to all our parents, teachers, admin, and community for their support through the fall semester. These students have worked incredibly hard, and we couldn’t have done it without y’all!

After 5 months of practice and competition, the 18-19 CDE season has officially come to an end for the Winona FFA. The highlights:

- 5 teams/18 students participating at the Area contest
- 3 State Qualifying Teams
- 1 team 11th in the State (MQP)
- 1 team qualifying for State that never existed before in Winona (Ento)
- 1 team improving their State performance by more than 100 points (Vet Sci)
- 1 team finishing 7th in Area 6 with all 8th graders (Poultry)
- 3,300 miles traveled (approximately)
- 3 Ag Teachers extremely blessed to be working with our Winona students, parents, admin, colleagues, school board, and community members!

The Team:

Milk Quality Products: Jocelyn Chavez, Jimena Tangassi, Sydney Burnham, Mackenzi Green

Veterinary Science: Shay Barrett, Brilen Seratte, Kaylee Collins

Entomology: Jose Madrid, JJ Barrera, Alejandro Martinez, Miranda Lopez

Nursery/Landscape: Keyona Nathaniel, Carter Perryman, Savannah Woodall

Poultry Judging: Courtney Green, Bailee Wilson, Blair Soop, Laura Rodriguez

shared_text:
Robert Reynolds
April 25, 2019 at 9:39 PM ·

Success is often measured by growth. For some the growth measured by these young may seem as baby steps! For me I have watched grow to unmeasurable heights. Today these special girls fell one spot short of a goal they set to be in the top ten at the state milk quality contest. After initial tears the conversation on the ride home became lighter and the car filled with singing and laughter. I truly don’t know if they realize the impact they have had on their ag. teachers and their program. I could be more proud of them. The placing means little but the talks about college, next year, goals, maybe being an ag teacher has allowed me to even more of the decision to return to ag. Teaching. Winona proud thank you Jocelyn, Jimena, Sydney and Mackenzi

A good day for Winona FFA! Our next LDE Contest will be Saturday in Waskom.

post_text: An awesome read that describes what we’re all about in FFA.
shared_text:
TEXASLONESTARONLINE.ORG
Texas Lone Star - AUGUST 2018 - 14

Texas FFA Foundation
August 8, 2018 at 8:24 PM ·

The FFA doesn’t point kids in just one direction—it gives them direction. The world needs innovators, leaders, and workers who are ready and willing to get the job done, and Texas agriscience education and the FFA are preparing them for the challenges ahead.

The blue and gold FFA jacket is about so much more than farming. When a student puts on the FFA jacket, an almost endless horizon of opportunities appears. In a world where students are trying to find their space and their voice, FFA offers something for everyone.

Read and share this article from the Texas Association of School Boards (TASB) magazine - a first for the Texas FFA.

http://www.texaslonestaronline.org/texaslonestar/august_2018?pg=14#pg14
